            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Ricardo Solis is a man who understands San Francisco from the ground up\u2014literally from the curb. His upbringing in the city\u2019s Excelsior district was a blend of practical grit and quiet style. His father, a second-generation Mexican-American mechanic, taught him the soul of an engine and the value of an honest day's work. His mother, who immigrated from Spain, instilled in him a subtle flair and the importance of presentation. School was never Ricardo\u2019s arena; he was a hands-on learner who found classrooms stifling, and he was relieved to earn his diploma and enter the workforce.\n\nHis career began by chance. At 19, he took a job parking cars at a popular restaurant, and something clicked. It wasn\u2019t just about driving; it was a performance. He had an uncanny ability to remember faces, cars, and small personal details. He moved from restaurants to luxury hotels, learning the art of discretion and seamless service. The key turning point was his promotion to Lead Valet at a prestigious, members-only club in Nob Hill. Suddenly, he was managing a team, orchestrating the chaotic ballet of arrivals and departures for the city's elite. At $88,000, his income is a testament to his expertise and the trust he\u2019s earned.\n\nRicardo\u2019s life is one of disciplined routine. His 6.5-mile commute on the Muni from his modest Inner Richmond apartment is his time to decompress before the evening rush. He lives with his long-term girlfriend, Maya, a paralegal who shares his pragmatic view of life. Their evenings are quiet, a stark contrast to the high-stakes world he navigates at work.\n\nSocially, he keeps a tight circle of friends from his old neighborhood, ensuring he stays grounded. His connection to San Francisco is profound; he sees the city\u2019s dualities every day, from the working-class heart of his youth to the polished veneer of his profession. His dream isn\u2019t to join the ranks of the tech millionaires he serves, but to save enough to launch his own boutique valet service\u2014one built on the principles of respect and perfection his parents taught him. He wants to own his piece of the city, not through stock options, but through unparalleled service, one car at a time."
